bush administration officials said thursday 
they hope food aid can soon resume flowing to sudan but they 
strongly criticized the government of the faminewracked african 
nation 
to put it bluntly the relief situation has deteriorated 
assistant secretary of state herman j cohen told a joint hearing 
of the house foreign affairs subcommittee on africa and a task 
force on hunger 
cohen who visited the african nation last week said a civil 
war between the government and separatists in the south has blocked 
international relief agencies from shipping food into the country 
both sides in the current conflict say they want peace 
but both continue to fight he said 
three million sudanese are homeless and 500000 are at risk of 
death as a result of war and famine some 250000 many of them 
children died last year 
the united states joined other nations last year in operation 
lifeline sudan washington contributed more than 60 percent of the 
food delivered at a cost of 72 million 
the project succeeded in part because of a ceasefire between 
government troops and the sudanese peoples liberation army but the 
spla broke the ceasefire last october and the fighting continued 
a number of actions by the government have so far severely 
hampered a resumption of last years successful operation cohen 
said the spla must share the blame for this deterioration 
foreign donors are attempting to negotiate with the sudanese 
government to begin another round of operation lifeline sudan 
while we cannot say that the relief effort is definitely back 
on track we hope that it will be shortly cohen said i am 
confident that the sudanese government will fulfill its pledge to 
cooperate on operation lifeline sudan 
