<TEXT>
lodging expenses for healthrelated travel are 
taxdeductible only if necessary to obtain a physicians care the 
us tax court has ruled 
merely traveling on a doctors recommendation to a more 
favorable climate to alleviate a specific ailment is not enough to 
justify a deduction the court held the travel must be essential 
to care provided by a doctor in a hospital or similar facility 
the ruling earlier this week was the first time the court had 
considered a 1984 law that in certain situations allows lodging 
costs to be included in deductible medical expenses 
the court case involved earlene polyak of trenton mich who 
suffered from chronic heart artery and lung problems following 
her doctors advice she began spending winters in florida living 
in a travel trailer while her husband stayed at their home in 
michigan 
her physicians did not refer mrs polyak to any doctors in 
florida and she visited a doctor only twice during her five months 
there 
she and her husband claimed a medical deduction for 1426 they 
spent to rent a campground lot for the trailer but were turned down 
by the internal revenue service 
the new law was written to benefit people who must travel away 
from home because specialized care is not available locally or in 
the case of some chemotherapy treatment for cancer for example 
may be obtained on an outpatient basis at a considerably lower 
cost 
in siding with the irs against mrs polyak senior judge william 
a goffe noted the new law permits deduction of transportation 
costs in such cases so long as it is primarily for and essential 
to medical care but lodging expenses must pass a threepart test 
they must be primarily for and essential to medical care 
the care must be provided by a physician in a licensed hospital 
or equivalent facility and 
the travel and lodging must hold no significant element of 
personal pleasure recreation or vacation 
goffe concluded that mrs polyak passed the first and third 
tests but failed the second 
mrs polyak did not go to florida to seek medical care from a 
physician goffe wrote the medical treatment received by mrs 
polyak was incidental and of routine nature 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

