<TEXT>
a surprise nationwide sweep of fastfood 
restaurants and other businesses found 7000 teenagers employed 
for too many hours or in dangerous jobs in violation of childlabor 
laws labor secretary elizabeth dole said thursday 
the threeday investigation called operation child watch 
is expected to result in more than 18 million in civil fines 
against businesses mrs dole said fines totaling 27 million 
were assessed during all of 1989 
the majority of the allegations involved firms in which 14 and 
15yearolds worked more hours or later at night during the school 
week than allowed under federal law said william brooks an 
assistant labor secretary 
but there were also more than 900 youngsters mostly 16 and 
17yearolds who were performing dangerous tasks or using 
hazardous equipment such as powerdriven meatslicing machinery 
dough mixers and paperbalers 
mrs dole said labor shortages are tempting firms to violate 
childlabor laws in order to find enough workers that problem will 
only worsen in coming years she said since the number of workers 
between the ages of 16 and 24 is expected to drop by about 2 
million or 8 percent by the year 2000 
she said businesses may need to consider offering better fringe 
benefits and higher salaries in order to attract workers 
federal law forbids 14yearolds and 15yearolds from working 
more than three hours on a school day or 18 hours during the 
fiveday school week eight hours is permitted on weekend days and 
40hour weeks are permitted in summer and during vacations 
those youngsters may not work outside the hours of 7 am to 7 
pm or 9 pm from june 1 to labor day 
brooks also said nearly 200 youngsters under 14 barred from 
most jobs with a few exceptions such as certain farm work and 
newspaper routes were found illegally employed 
most of the 7000 alleged violations were at service businesses 
such as restaurants grocery stores pizza and donut shops or dry 
cleaning firms officials said 
mrs dole declined to name businesses involved saying 
investigations are still going on 
brooks said one food store employed more than 20 minors whose 
duties included the operation of paperbaling machinery which he 
called a particularly dangerous piece of equipment pizza shops 
in two states employed more than 50 youngsters to illegally drive 
cars he said 
two 16yearolds were found illegally employed at a roofing 
company he said one of the youngsters fingers were crushed and 
nearly severed when a load shifted on the back of a truck the 
other boy had fallen off a roof but did not sustain longterm 
injuries brooks said 
the threeday probe which involved 500 federal investigators 
who visited businesses in all 50 states was intended to send a 
signal that the government is strengthening its efforts to protect 
children from exploitation in the workplace mrs dole said at a 
news conference 
the cop is on the beat violations whether motivated by greed 
or by ignorance will not be tolerated she said 
mrs dole said skeptics of the bush administrations commitment 
to child labor enforcement are needlessly worried 
i think the proof is in the pudding as they say there will 
be additional strike forces she said 
in a letter to mrs dole this week rep charles schumer 
dny called for more money to combat childlabor violations he 
noted that there are fewer than 1000 federal investigators 
assigned to such matters 
with so little oversight it is little wonder than childlabor 
violations are becoming more widespread in the absence of 
strong federal action the future may be even bleaker schumer 
wrote 
rep don pease dohio said he welcomed mrs doles readiness 
to get tough with child labor scofflaws but said the situation 
calls for more than a finger in the dike 
pease and schumer plan to introduce legislation next month to 
expand the definition of childlabor violations it also may 
provide more funding for enforcement and increase the penalties 
beyond the current 1000 maximum a spokesman said 
mrs dole said the government should first make the most of 
current resources then if additional funds are needed you can 
bet ill ask for those funds she said adding that other 
proposed changes are under review 
of the 3400 businesses visited during the threeday probe 
about 1400 were in apparent violation of child labor practices 
she said 
last year the labor departments wage and hour division which 
enforces childlabor provisions of the fair labor standards act 
found 22508 minors to be illegally employed an alltime high 
last thursday the department sued the burger king restaurant 
chain in us district court in miami alleging child labor law 
violations since 1986 
