<TEXT>
during his 16 years on the road trucker 
roosevelt jones had to rely on telephones to contact his company 
often phoning dispatchers thousands of miles away to report trouble 
or receive instructions 
now without leaving his rig he can send and receive messages 
in seconds using a satellite system that is revolutionizing the 
trucking industry 
besides providing speedy communications the system features 
special truck transmitters that enable dispatchers to monitor each 
vehicles travels and pinpoint its location customers can get 
hourly updates on the status of shipments 
all the folks that have them in their trucks seem to like 
them said jones a driver for wingatetaylor maid transportation 
inc a subsidiary of burlington motor carriers 
burlington the nations fourthlargest truck load carrier is 
installing the satellite system in 2000 trucks operated by its 
four subsidiaries wingatetailor maid of albany ga stoops 
express of anderson ind monroe trucking of monroe la and 
monkem of joplin mo 
joanne rang executive director of the american trucking 
association said satellite tracking is still relatively new and 
represents a substantial investment for companies firms willing to 
make the investment should be able to monitor shipments more 
closely and provide better service to their customers she said in 
an interview from her alexandria va office 
mike hodson burlingtons vice president for quality said the 
company evaluated several systems before selecting one developed by 
hughes network systems of germantown md 
during an eightmonth study burlington trucks equipped with 
satellite communications ran more miles ran fewer empty miles and 
ran the most direct routes hodson said in a phone interview from 
his hurst texas office 
the system proved it could reduce waste lower operating costs 
give burlington a competitive edge and improve its drivers quality 
of life he said 
drivers who rely on phones have to interrupt trips to check in 
with their companies they call from truck stops rest areas or any 
other place with safe parking 
after delivering their cargos they often have to phone 
dispatchers repeatedly sometimes for lengthy periods for 
instructions on picking up new loads 
he ends up at some truck stop drinking coffee smoking 
cigarettes shooting the breeze hodson said now he can sleep 
and wait for a beeper to go off we think its going to create a 
safer fleet because the guys are going to be better rested 
the burlington drivers communicate via a small keyboard that 
displays messages on a tiny screen they can select routine 
messages and fill in blank spaces with details or type in special 
messages for safety the truckers cant send messages while 
driving 
the message is beamed to a satellite and then down to a dish 
antenna in washington dc where it is decoded it then is sent 
back to the satellite and down to burlingtons message center in 
joplin mo from there it is relayed to the subsidiaries by 
telephone line 
dispatchers sitting at computer terminals can communicate with 
drivers or ask the computer to list the locations of all trucks 
they are supervising 
its going to improve our efficiency said mike driggers 
wingatetailor maids vice president of operations 
as driver jones prepared to make his first trip with the new 
system he met with instructor rodney hogan to learn how to operate 
the keyboard and transmit messages 
it seems kind of odd to me because i never used it before 
he said before pointing his white freightliner toward amarillo 
tex once i get used to it i think ill like it better than a 
phone 
</TEXT>
