saks fifth avenues management and japans tobu 
department store co ltd thursday said they submitted a joint 
buyout proposal for the 46store chain 
here is a brief history of saks 
saks was the brainchild of horace saks and bernard gimbel who 
independently operated stores in new york city in the early part of 
this century the two merchants decided to open a fashionable 
specialty department store catering to the carriage trade the 
store on fifth avenue opened sept 15 1924 
from 1924 to 1969 saks expanded and built a national 
recognition as an upscale retailer mainly of fashionable apparel 
bernard gimbels cousin adam became president after the 
sudden death of horace saks in 1926 under adam gimbel branch 
stores were opened and the flagship manhattan store was redecorated 
in the opulent art moderne style from the 1925 paris exposition 
adam gimbel retired as saks president in 1969 at the time 
there were 21 saks stores 
saks in 1973 was bought by batus inc the us holding 
company of the londonbased conglomerate bat indusries plc 
under bats ownership saks has grown to include 46 stores 
operating in 33 markets in 20 states states in which there are 
saks stores include arizona california connecticut florida 
georgia illinois louisana maryland massachusetts michigan 
minnesota missouri nevada new jersey new york ohio oklahoma 
pennsylvania texas and virginia 
the flagship fifth avenue store was proclaimed a new york city 
landmark in 1985 
bat announced in september 1989 plans to sell saks its other 
retailing operations plus certain other assets as part of a 
strategy to thwart an unsolicited takeover attempt by an investment 
group led by the anglofrench financier sir james goldsmith the 
22 billion bid for bat has been suspended pending the outcome of a 
review by us insurance regulatory agencies expected in the 
coming months 
