<TEXT>
personal bankruptcies have jumped by 31 percent in 
new england more rapidly than any other region reflecting a 
softening regional economy that also has taken its toll on banks 
and businesses 
analysts say bankruptcies once considered by some the refuge of 
highflyers who play the game and lose are becoming the resort of 
new englands average joes who get caught between pervasive 
layoffs a daunting debt load and plunging real estate values 
im not surprised by the fact that this is happening all of a 
sudden the door is closed said edward j powers who studies new 
england as a consulting economist with william witter inc a new 
yorkbased pension fund management company a lot of people here 
are two paychecks away from bankruptcy even though this is 
supposed to be a conservative region 
in 1988 personal bankruptcies totalled 25417 in new york and 
the six new england states figures from the us district courts 
show in 1989 that number rose to 33294 an increase of 31 
percent 
new hampshire led the list of the seven states with an increase 
in personal bankruptcies of 55 percent while in massachusetts the 
increase was 50 percent on the other end of the scale vermont 
actually showed a decrease of 4 percent 
compared to new england the next highest increase in personal 
bankruptcies was seen in the district including alabama florida 
and georgia where the figure rose 27 percent from 63139 to 80271 
personal bankruptcies have risen only 12 percent nationwide to 
616753 court figures show 
in ordinary times personal bankruptcies stem most often from a 
major medical illness said judy kent of the american fiscal 
services association in washington dc a financial services 
trade association which compiled the figures in addition to bad 
budgeting divorce and job loss can also lead an individual to file 
proceedings kent said 
in new england however the rise in personal bankruptcies comes 
as the region hurtles downward from the boom years in the 1980s 
when its four main industries hightech construction defense 
and financial services took off those industries have largely 
contracted with revenues falling off and widespread layoffs 
announced 
we had the fastest rise in personal bankruptcies in part 
because we had such a booming economy for so long said wayne 
ayers chief economist with the bank of boston when things slow 
down they often slow down with a vengeance 
there hasnt been a rise in major medical illnesses in new 
england said david wyss chief economist for data resources an 
economic research group in lexington rather wyss says the region 
is seeing more bankruptcies because of the soft real estate and job 
markets here 
its the average joe who is caught up in this relatively 
young with little or no assets and who borrowed heavily to buy 
his first home and now hes caught said wyss 
in massachusetts the unemployment rate has gone from 35 
percent in november 1988 to 53 percent in february 1990 a rise 
mimicked throughout the region 
a lot of people had of course acquired consumer debt and 
household debt and when you lose your job you cant pay it they 
cannot pay the debts they undertook in better times wyss said 
major employers such as wang laboratories inc digital 
equipment corp and general electric co have laid off thousands of 
workers and the financial services industry has cut back 20 
percent of its jobs in new england powers said those layoffs have 
led to job losses at barber shops restaurants and clothing stores 
powers said 
bankruptcy happens he said in high pockets of unemployment 
where people are overwhelmed when the downturn surrounds them 
inside their region how can you sell anything its just very 
difficult 
changes in law have also made declaring bankruptcy less 
financially painful analysts said the deals each debtor strikes 
still depends on how creditors litigators and judges assess the 
depth of his fiscal desperation but now in many cases people can 
keep their house and car powers said 
analysts agreed declaring bankruptcy had also lost some of the 
disgrace it carried years ago though they acknowledged it was a 
process most people wanted to avoid 
in japan people commit suicide rather than file bankruptcy 
its the ultimate disgrace its called seppuku said powers 
whereas over here its not immoral or disgraceful anymore its 
part of the culture now 
there has been an increase in the willingness of people to go 
bankrupt said wyss of data resources there is not as much 
stigma they can continue to work and probably get a new credit 
card tomorrow 
