<TEXT>
talks with the japanese on a key trade dispute 
involving purchases of american satellites broke off this week 
after zero progress had been made a disappointed us trade 
official told reporters thursday 
the official said that no further talks would be held unless the 
japanese budge from their current position 
the talks this week have been dancing in circles without 
getting anywhere near the destination and the music is about to run 
out said the official who briefed reporters on condition that 
his name not be used 
satellites are one of three us product groups that have been 
targeted for the removal of trade barriers by the japanese if 
significant progress has not been made by june 15 the 
administration has the power to retaliate by imposing higher 
tariffs on japanese products 
the official said that discussions in the other two areas 
american lumber products and supercomputers were apparently 
making some progress but that the discussion on satellites was 
the sore thumb it is sticking out 
the talks on specific products being held under a toughened 
portion of the trade law known as super 301 are one of the key 
avenues the administration is pursuing in an effort to reduce the 
huge 49 billion trade deficit with japan 
japanese negotiators met with us officials in washington for 
two days on the satellite issue earlier this week the talks moved 
to wood products on thursday and were to address supercomputers 
early next week 
the satellite talks marked the fourth time negotiators had met 
on this issue since last summer the american side is seeking 
assurances that the japanese government which is responsible for 
the bulk of satellite purchases in japan will stop favoring 
japanese firms in the bidding process 
the negotiator said that the united states is willing to exempt 
research and development efforts by the japanese who want to 
promote their own space industry however he said japanese 
negotiators were insisting that virtually all satellite projects 
fell under the definition of basic research 
the us trade official said he had told his japanese 
counterparts that another meeting on satellites would be a waste of 
time unless the japanese position changed 
we made zero progress at this meeting he said if they 
call up with a new proposal and it looks like there is some meat 
there then we will meet again 
in addition to the talks on satellites supercomputers and wood 
products the administration has launched discussions aimed at 
removing more broadbased barriers to trade in both countries the 
next round of talks on socalled strucutral impediments are 
scheduled to be held in washington on april 2 and 3 but so far 
little progress has been made in these discussions 
president bush and japanese prime minister toshiki kaifu met in 
palm springs calif recently with both leaders pledging renewed 
efforts to reach compromises in the various trade disputes 
